[{"issueId":"64449ae9-2aaa-41f7-a6c0-c132c3f55c11","aiExplanation":"This color contrast issue means text on the page doesn't have enough visual distinction from its background. Users with low vision, color blindness, or those viewing the screen in bright lighting conditions may struggle or be unable to read the text. The detected contrast ratio of 3.5:1 falls below the WCAG AA requirement of 4.5:1 for normal-sized text, making the content potentially illegible for approximately 8% of men and 0.5% of women who have some form of color vision deficiency.","aiFixSuggestion":"Increase the contrast between the text color and background color to achieve at least a 4.5:1 ratio for normal text (or 3:1 for large text 18pt+).

Before:
<p class="low-contrast">Sample text with low contrast</p>

After (adjust colors in CSS):
.low-contrast {
  color: #595959; /* Darker gray instead of light gray */
  background-color: #ffffff; /* Ensure background is defined */
}

Use a contrast checker tool like WebAIM's Contrast Checker (https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/) to verify your color combinations meet the 4.5:1 minimum ratio. For the Zimbra login page, review the form labels, placeholder text, and any informational text for compliance.","aiPriority":8},{"issueId":"a2e0c138-1c57-4931-8576-f3878befa90f","aiExplanation":"This image is missing alternative text, which means screen reader users will have no information about what the image conveys. Depending on the image's purpose, users may miss important visual information, branding context, or functional cues. Screen readers typically announce these images as just 'image' or read out the filename, which provides no meaningful information. For a login page, if this is the company logo, users won't know which service they're signing into.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add an alt attribute that describes the image's purpose and content. The appropriate alt text depends on the image's function:

For an informative logo:
<img src="logo.png" alt="Zimbra Web Client">

For a decorative image (if it adds no information):
<img src="logo.png" alt="">

For a logo that serves as a link to home:
<img src="logo.png" alt="Zimbra - Return to home page">

Note: The current Zimbra login page actually handles this correctly with a screen-reader-only span containing 'Zimbra' text alongside the logo. Verify this pattern is used consistently across the application.","aiPriority":7},{"issueId":"5ae7ec80-0327-4153-8bca-69e5bc05aa0b","aiExplanation":"This link contains only an icon with no text alternative, making it impossible for screen reader users to understand the link's purpose or destination. When a screen reader encounters this link, it may announce nothing, just 'link', or the unhelpful href value. Users relying on assistive technology cannot make an informed decision about whether to activate this link, effectively hiding functionality from them. This also affects voice control users who cannot speak a command to activate the link.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add accessible text to the link using one of these methods:

Option 1 - Add visually hidden text (recommended for icon-only links):
<a href="/page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
  <span class="visually-hidden">Description of link destination</span>
</a>

Option 2 - Add aria-label:
<a href="/page" aria-label="Description of link destination">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
</a>

Option 3 - Add title attribute (less preferred, not announced by all screen readers):
<a href="/page" title="Description of link destination">
  <i class="icon"></i>
</a>

CSS for visually-hidden class:
.visually-hidden {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;
}","aiPriority":6}]
